ğŸ’¡ Follow-up: Iterative Stack-based Solution
ğŸ¯ Goal
Build the BST without recursion â€” using a stack to simulate the recursive behavior.

ğŸ§  Core Idea
Letâ€™s recall preorder traversal order:
â¡ï¸ Root â†’ Left â†’ Right

And BST property:
â¡ï¸ Left child < parent < right child

Now, while iterating preorder, we can use a stack to keep track of ancestors.

ğŸ” Intuition (Step-by-step)
The first element of preorder is always the root.
Push it into the stack.

For every new element val in preorder:

If val < stack.top()->val,
â‡’ itâ€™s left child of the top node.
(Just attach and push it.)

Else
â‡’ pop until stack is empty or top node has a greater value.
The last popped node is the parent, and val is its right child.

Repeat for all nodes.

ğŸ§© Dry Run Example
Input: preorder = [8, 5, 1, 7, 10, 12]

Step	Value	Stack (top â†’ bottom)	Action	Tree Change
1	8	[8]	root = 8	(root created)
2	5	[5, 8]	5 < 8 â‡’ left child	5 â†’ left of 8
3	1	[1, 5, 8]	1 < 5 â‡’ left child	1 â†’ left of 5
4	7	[7, 8]	7 > 1, 7 > 5 â‡’ pop 1, 5 â†’ right child	7 â†’ right of 5
5	10	[10]	10 > 8 â‡’ pop 7, 8 â†’ right child	10 â†’ right of 8
6	12	[12, 10]	12 > 10 â‡’ right child	12 â†’ right of 10

âœ… Final Tree:

markdown
Copy code
        8
       / \
      5   10
     / \    \
    1   7    12
ğŸ’» Iterative C++ Code
cpp
Copy code
class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* bstFromPreorder(vector<int>& preorder) {
        if (preorder.empty()) return nullptr;

        TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(preorder[0]);
        stack<TreeNode*> st;
        st.push(root);

        for (int i = 1; i < preorder.size(); i++) {
            TreeNode* temp = nullptr;

            // Pop until we find parent for current node
            while (!st.empty() && preorder[i] > st.top()->val) {
                temp = st.top();
                st.pop();
            }

            TreeNode* node = new TreeNode(preorder[i]);
            if (temp) {
                // If temp != nullptr, current node is right child
                temp->right = node;
            } else {
                // Else, current node is left child of top of stack
                st.top()->left = node;
            }

            // Push new node into stack
            st.push(node);
        }

        return root;
    }
};
âš™ï¸ Complexity Analysis
Complexity	Value	Reason
Time	O(N)	Each node pushed/popped at most once
Space	O(H)	Stack stores path of current ancestors (H â‰¤ N)

ğŸ§© Comparison Table
Approach	Type	Time	Space	When to Use
Recursive (Naive Split)	Recursive	O(NÂ²)	O(N)	When learning conceptually
Recursive (Bounded)	Recursive	O(N)	O(H)	Cleanest & most optimal
Iterative (Stack)	Iterative	O(N)	O(H)	When interviewer says "no recursion"

ğŸ§  Pattern Connection
Problem	Key Idea
1008. Construct BST from Preorder	Stack or recursion with bound
449. Serialize & Deserialize BST	Same bound logic
701. Insert into BST	Recursion with BST property
230. Kth Smallest in BST	Inorder traversal pattern
98. Validate BST	Range (min, max) pattern

ğŸ§  Interview Summary
Typical Dialogue:

Interviewer: Can you now do it iteratively without recursion?
Candidate: Yes. We can simulate the recursion stack using a stack of nodes.
For each node, if the next preorder value is smaller, itâ€™s the left child;
if itâ€™s greater, pop until we find where it fits as a right child.
This ensures O(N) time and O(H) space.

âœ… Final Key Takeaway

ğŸ‘‰ Recursive bounded and Iterative stack-based solutions both run in O(N).
Remember: Preorder â†’ â€œUpper Boundâ€ approach, Postorder â†’ â€œLower Boundâ€ approach.

