ğŸ§© Construct Binary Search Tree from Postorder Traversal (LeetCode-style variation: 1028 & classic postorder â†’ BST)

This is a favorite follow-up after you solve 1008 (preorder â†’ BST) because it tests whether youâ€™ve internalized how traversal order affects recursion direction and boundary management.

ğŸš€ Problem Setup (Postorder Version)
Problem Statement
Given the postorder traversal of a Binary Search Tree (BST), reconstruct the BST.

Example:

yaml
Copy code
Input: postorder = [1, 7, 5, 12, 10, 8]
Output Tree:
        8
       / \
      5   10
     / \    \
    1   7    12
ğŸ§© Step 1: Recall the Traversal Orders
Traversal Type	Order of Nodes
Preorder	Root â†’ Left â†’ Right
Postorder	Left â†’ Right â†’ Root

So when constructing from postorder, we must process nodes from the end (Root) backwards.

ğŸ¯ Key Idea (Mirror of Preorder Approach)
When we built from preorder, we used an upper bound to decide when a node doesn't belong to the current subtree.

For postorder, we go backwards (right â†’ left â†’ root).
So weâ€™ll use a lower bound instead of an upper bound.

ğŸ” Recursive Logic
Recurrence Function
sql
Copy code
build(postorder, lowerBound):
    if i < 0 or postorder[i] < lowerBound:
        return NULL
    
    root = new TreeNode(postorder[i--])
    root->right = build(postorder, root->val)
    root->left = build(postorder, lowerBound)
    return root
ğŸ’¡ Notice we first build the right subtree, because in postorder (leftâ€“rightâ€“root), when reversed, we see rootâ€“rightâ€“left (similar to preorder, but reversed).

ğŸ’» Code Implementation (Recursive Optimal)
cpp
Copy code
class Solution {
public:
    int i;
    
    TreeNode* bstFromPostorder(vector<int>& postorder) {
        i = postorder.size() - 1;  // start from the end
        return build(postorder, INT_MIN);
    }

    TreeNode* build(vector<int>& postorder, int lowerBound) {
        if (i < 0 || postorder[i] < lowerBound)
            return nullptr;

        TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(postorder[i--]);
        // build right first, then left (reverse of postorder)
        root->right = build(postorder, root->val);
        root->left = build(postorder, lowerBound);
        return root;
    }
};
