âš¡ Iterative Version (Stack-based)
You can also do it iteratively like the preorder version â€” but reversed traversal order.

Logic:
Traverse from end â†’ start

Maintain a stack to keep ancestors.

Keep track of the last popped node to attach as left child.

C++ Code:
cpp
Copy code
class Solution {
public:
    TreeNode* bstFromPostorder(vector<int>& postorder) {
        if (postorder.empty()) return nullptr;

        TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(postorder.back());
        stack<TreeNode*> st;
        st.push(root);

        for (int i = postorder.size() - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            TreeNode* temp = nullptr;

            while (!st.empty() && postorder[i] < st.top()->val) {
                temp = st.top();
                st.pop();
            }

            TreeNode* node = new TreeNode(postorder[i]);
            if (temp) temp->left = node;
            else st.top()->right = node;

            st.push(node);
        }

        return root;
    }
};
ğŸ§© Comparison Summary
Approach	Order	Bound Used	Build Order	Time	Space
Preorder BST	Rootâ€“Leftâ€“Right	Upper Bound	Left â†’ Right	O(N)	O(H)
Postorder BST	Leftâ€“Rightâ€“Root	Lower Bound	Right â†’ Left	O(N)	O(H)

ğŸ§  Pattern Trick to Remember
Traversal	Direction	Bound	Build Order
Preorder	Forward	Upper Bound	Left then Right
Postorder	Backward	Lower Bound	Right then Left

ğŸ’¡ Memory Hook:

â€œPre â†’ Upper, Post â†’ Lowerâ€

Thatâ€™s how you remember which bound to use.

