ğŸ§© 105. Construct Binary Tree from Preorder and Inorder Traversal
ğŸ¯ Problem Statement
Youâ€™re given two integer arrays:

preorder[] â€” preorder traversal of a binary tree (Root â†’ Left â†’ Right)

inorder[] â€” inorder traversal of the same tree (Left â†’ Root â†’ Right)

Build and return the binary tree.

ğŸ§  Example
makefile
Copy code
Input:
preorder = [3,9,20,15,7]
inorder  = [9,3,15,20,7]

Output Tree:
        3
       / \
      9   20
          / \
         15  7
ğŸ’¬ Interviewerâ€“Candidate Conversation
Interviewer:
Youâ€™re given preorder and inorder traversals of a binary tree. Can you reconstruct it?

Candidate:
Yes â€” preorder gives me the root at each step, and inorder tells me which elements go to the left and right subtrees.

ğŸ§© Step 1: Understand the Relationship Between Traversals
Traversal	Order	What it tells us
Preorder	Root â†’ Left â†’ Right	First element = root
Inorder	Left â†’ Root â†’ Right	Position of root divides tree into left & right subtrees

ğŸ” Recursive Approach (Core Idea)
Algorithm:
Use a global index preIndex to track the current element in preorder.

Use a hashmap to store the index of each value in inorder for O(1) lookups.

Pick preorder[preIndex] as root.

Split the inorder array into left and right parts using this rootâ€™s position.

Recursively build left and right subtrees.

ğŸ§® Recurrence Relation
scss
Copy code
build(preL, preR, inL, inR):
    root = preorder[preL]
    inRoot = index[root] in inorder
    leftSize = inRoot - inL

    root->left  = build(preL+1, preL+leftSize, inL, inRoot-1)
    root->right = build(preL+leftSize+1, preR, inRoot+1, inR)
ğŸ’» C++ Code (Optimal Recursive)
cpp
Copy code
class Solution {
public:
    unordered_map<int, int> inorderIndex;
    int preIndex = 0;

    TreeNode* buildTree(vector<int>& preorder, vector<int>& inorder) {
        // Store inorder value â†’ index mapping for O(1) access
        for (int i = 0; i < inorder.size(); i++)
            inorderIndex[inorder[i]] = i;

        return build(preorder, inorder, 0, inorder.size() - 1);
    }

    TreeNode* build(vector<int>& preorder, vector<int>& inorder, int inStart, int inEnd) {
        if (inStart > inEnd) return nullptr;

        // Pick current node from preorder
        int rootVal = preorder[preIndex++];
        TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(rootVal);

        // Find position in inorder
        int idx = inorderIndex[rootVal];

        // Build left and right subtrees
        root->left = build(preorder, inorder, inStart, idx - 1);
        root->right = build(preorder, inorder, idx + 1, inEnd);

        return root;
    }
};
